page.title: Objects
page.text: Programs work with data. Every piece of data in a Python program is called an \dred{object}.
Objects can be very small (the number \dred{3}) or very large (a digital photograph).
Every object has a \dred{type}. The type determines what you can do with an object.

The \dred{Python Zoo}:\\ Imagine there is a zoo inside your Python interpreter. \\ Every time you create an object, an animal is born.\\ What an animal can do depends on the type (kind) of animal: birds can fly, fish can swim, elephants can lift weights, etc.\\ When an animal is no longer used, it dies (disappears).

page.title: Making objects
page.text: You can create objects as follows:
\dred{Numbers}: Simply write them: \begin{V} 13 3.14159265 -5 3 + 6j \end{V}
complex number
\dred{Booleans}: (truth values)\\ Write |True| or |False|.

page.title: Making more objects
page.text:
A \dred{tuple} object is an object that contains other objects.\\ To create a tuple, write objects separated by commas (usually in parenthesis):
\begin{V} (3, 2.5, 7) ("red", "yellow", "green") (20100001, "Hong Gildong") \end{V}

page.title: Different animals: Types
page.text: Every object has a \dred{type}. The type determines what the object can do, and what you can do with the object. For instance, you can add two numbers, but you cannot add two robots.

The Python interpreter can tell you the type of an object:
\begin{V} >>> type(3) <type 'int'> >>> type(3.1415) <type 'float'> >>> type("CS101 is fantastic") <type 'str'> >>> type(3 + 7j) <type 'complex'> >>> type(True) <type 'bool'> \end{V}
Integer number: \dred{int}
Floating point number: \dred{float}
String: \dred{str}
Complex number: \dred{complex}
Boolean: \dred{bool}

page.title: More types
page.text:
Types of more complicated objects:
\begin{V} >>> type(Robot()) <class 'cs1robots.Robot'> >>> type( (3, -1.5, 7) ) <type 'tuple'> >>> type( load_picture() ) <class 'cs1media.Picture'> \end{V}

Some object types are built into the Python language: |<type 'xxx'>|
Other object types are defined by Python modules: |<class 'xxx'>|

page.title: Names
page.text:
Objects can be given a \dred{name}:
\begin{V} message = "CS101 is fantastic" n = 17 hubo = Robot() pi = 3.1415926535897931 finished = True img = load_picture("geowi.jpg") \end{V}
We call a statement like |n = 17| an \dred{assignment}, because the \dred{name} |n| is \dred{assigned} to the object |17|.
In the Python zoo, the name is a sign board on the animal's cage.

page.title: Variable names
page.text:
The rules for variable and function names:
\begin{itemize} \item A name consists of letters, digits, and the underscore |_|. \item The first character of a name is a letter. \item The name cannot be a keyword such as |def|, |if|, |else|, or |while|. \item Upper case and lower case are different: |Pi| is not the same as |pi|. \end{itemize}

page.title: Variables
page.text: In the Python zoo, this means that the sign board is moved from one animal to a different animal.
The object assigned to a name is called the \dred{value} of the variable. The value can change over time.

page.title: Methods
page.text: What objects can do depends on the type of object: a bird can fly, a fish can swim.\\ Objects provide \dred{methods} to perform these actions.

page.text:
\dred{Warning:} In Python~2, the division operator |/| works like |//| if both objects are |int| objects. This has been fixed in Python~3:
\begin{V} >>> 9 / 7 1 >>> from __future__ import division >>> 9 / 7 1.2857142857142858 \end{V}
Remainder after division

page.title: Expressions
page.text: $\frac{a}{2\pi}$ is \dred{not} |a/2*pi|.
Use |a/(2*pi)| or |a/2/pi|.
All operators also work for complex numbers.

page.title: String expressions
page.text:
The operators |+| and |*| can be used for strings:
\begin{V} >>> "Hello" + "CS101" 'HelloCS101' >>> "CS101 " * 8 'CS101 CS101 CS101 CS101 CS101 CS101 CS101 CS101 ' \end{V}

page.title: Boolean expressions
page.text: A \dred{boolean expression} is an expression whose value has type |bool|. They are used in |if| and |while| statements.

The operators |==|, |!=|, |>|, |<|, |<=|, and |>=| return boolean values.
\begin{V} >>> 3 < 5 True >>> 27 == 14 False >>> 3.14 != 3.14 False >>> 3.14 >= 3.14 True >>> "Cheong" < "Choe" True >>> "3" == 3 False \end{V}
Equality---don't confuse with |=|

page.title: Logical operators
page.text:
The keywords |not|, |and|, and |or| are logical operators:
\begin{V} not True == False not False == True
False and False == False False and True == False True and False == False True and True == True
False or False == False False or True == True True or False == True True or True == True \end{V}
\dred{Careful:} if the second operand is not needed, Python does not even compute its value.
